During the California Gold Rush, water became a commodity controlled primarily by white miners. The state’s appropriative rights system allowed those who accessed water first to claim priority (i.e. “first in time, first in right”)(
Littleworth & Garner
). This rights system favored senior water rights holders, often wealthy landowners, and penalized junior rights holders and those without water rights at all—typically communities with less power or resources (
California Water Boards
). This Pre-1914 Water Rights system, along with the displacement of Indigenous people, entrenched an inequitable distribution of water contributed to the loss of Indigenous food sources and ways of life (
Plachta
,
SWB 2021
). At the same time, nearly two million white settlers received land titles under the Homestead Act and Desert Land Act (
Bork and Ziaja, 2023
), facilitating this concentration of water rights and resources. This system often excluded people of color by law—specifically Native Americans, Black Americans, Asian Americans and Mexican Americans—who were denied access to land and, by extension, water.

