## 2.4 Climate change is likely to exacerbate structural inequities

Climate change intensifies existing inequities in California’s historical water management systems. For example, sea-level rise and land subsidence threaten the Sacramento-San Joaquin Delta, the critical water conduit for the state, jeopardizing the water supply for millions of Californians and farms (
Hanak and Gartrell
). In addition, low-income and rural communities often rely on groundwater for drinking water, yet climate change is depleting aquifers and worsening water quality (cite?).

